Introduction to Kubernetes (K8s)
Kubernetes (or K8s) is an open-source platform used to deploy, manage, scale and automate containerized applications.
1. What is Container Orchestration?
Suppose your application runs in containers (for example using Docker).
One or two containers can be managed manually, but real applications may have hundreds or thousands of containers.
Container Orchestration means automatically managing those containers:


Where they should run


How many copies should run


Restart them if they fail


Scale them when traffic increases


Connect them with each other


Analogy:
Like an orchestra has many musicians and one conductor controls everyone, Kubernetes acts as the conductor for containers.
Without orchestration:


Manual deployments


Manual scaling


Server failures cause downtime


With Kubernetes:


Automated management


High availability


Self-healing systems



2. Why Kubernetes Needed?
Suppose your website suddenly gets huge traffic.
Problem 1: Traffic Spike
One server may crash under heavy load.
Kubernetes can:


Start more copies of your app (scaling)


Distribute users among them (load balancing)


Example:


1 server handles 1000 users


10,000 users arrive


Kubernetes can run 10 instances automatically.



Problem 2: Server Failure
Suppose a machine dies.
Normally:


App goes down.


With Kubernetes:


It detects failed containers.


Starts new ones automatically.


This is called Self-Healing.

3. Kubernetes Architecture
Kubernetes works on Master-Worker model.
(A) Master Node / Control Plane
This is the “brain”.
It doesn’t run your app usually—
it controls everything.
API Server
Main entry point of Kubernetes.
Whatever command you run:
kubectl apply -f app.yaml
goes to API server.
It receives requests and tells cluster what to do.
Think:


Front door of Kubernetes.



etcd
Distributed key-value database.
Stores:


Cluster state


Configurations


Running pods


Secrets


Everything important


Think:


Kubernetes memory/database.


If etcd gone → cluster in trouble.

Controller Manager
Controllers keep desired state = actual state.
Example:
You say:
“I want 3 pods running”
If one dies:


Controller notices only 2 running


Starts 1 new pod.


Maintains desired state.

Scheduler
Decides:
Which worker node should run a pod?
It checks:


CPU


Memory


Available resources


Like assigning students to classrooms.

(B) Worker Nodes
These do the real work.
Applications run here.

Kubelet
Agent on every worker node.
It:


Talks to master


Makes sure pods run


Restarts failed containers


Like node supervisor.

Kube Proxy
Handles networking.
Responsible for:


Routing traffic


Service communication


Load balancing inside cluster


Like traffic police.

Container Runtime
Software that actually runs containers.
Examples:


Docker


containerd


CRI-O


Without runtime containers can’t execute.

4. Pod (Most Important)
Smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes.
Not container directly—
Kubernetes deploys Pods, not raw containers.
A Pod can contain:


One container (common)


Multiple tightly coupled containers



Why Pod?
Because containers sometimes need helpers.
Example:
Main app container


logging sidecar container


Both in same pod.
They can:


Share network


Share storage


Talk via localhost



5. Important Features
Scalability
Increase/decrease instances automatically.
2 pods → 20 pods when traffic grows.

Zero Downtime
Update app without shutting service.
Users keep using app.
Called Rolling Updates.

Rollback
New version broken?
Return to old version instantly.

Self Healing
If container crashes:


restart


If node dies:


move workload elsewhere



6. YAML Configuration
Kubernetes resources are often defined in YAML.
Example:
apiVersion: v1kind: Podmetadata:  name: myappspec:  containers:  - name: app    image: nginx
Explanation:
apiVersion


Kubernetes API version


kind


What object you're creating
(Pod, Deployment, Service etc.)


metadata


Information like name


spec


Desired configuration


containers


Which container image to run


image: nginx
Uses Nginx container.
Apply:
kubectl apply -f app.yaml
Kubernetes creates it.

Full Flow
You write YAML
↓
Send with kubectl
↓
API Server receives it
↓
Scheduler chooses worker node
↓
Kubelet starts pod
↓
Container runtime runs container
↓
Kube Proxy exposes networking
↓
Controllers keep everything healthy
Whole system works together.

One-line Summary
Docker packages applications into containers. Kubernetes manages those containers at scale.


Docker = creates containers


Kubernetes = manages containers


